The '''squacco heron''' ('''''Ardeola ralloides''''') is a small [[heron]], {{convert|44|–|47|cm|in|frac=2|abbr=on}} long, of which the body is {{convert|20|–|23|cm|in|frac=2|abbr=on}}, with {{convert|80|–|92|cm|in|frac=2|abbr=on}} wingspan.<ref name=BWP/> It is of Old World origins, breeding in southern [[Europe]] and the [[Greater Middle East]].

==Behaviour==

The squacco heron is a [[bird migration|migrant]], wintering in [[Africa]]. It is rare north of its breeding range. The species has been recorded in [[Fernando de Noronha]] islands, and more rarely in mainland [[South America]], as a [[Vagrancy (biology)|vagrant]].

This is a stocky species with a short neck, short thick bill and buff-brown back. In summer, adults have long neck [[feather]]s. Its appearance is transformed in flight, when it looks very white due to the colour of the wings.

The squacco heron's breeding [[habitat (ecology)|habitat]] is marshy wetlands in warm countries. The birds nest in small colonies, often with other wading birds, usually on platforms of sticks in trees or shrubs. Three to four [[Egg (biology)|egg]]s are laid. They feed on fish, [[frog]]s and insects. The squacco heron is a host of the [[Acanthocephala]]n intestinal parasite ''[[Ardeirhynchus spiralis]]''.<ref name = Dimitrova1994>Dimitrova, Z. M., & Georgiev, B. B. (1994). Ardeirhynchus ng (Palaeacanthocephala: Polymorphida: Polymorphidae), with a redescription of A. spiralis (Rudolphi, 1809) n. comb. Systematic Parasitology, 29(2), 149-158.</ref>
